.\" lsof.1 - man page for lsof v5.0
.TH LSOF 1 "2026-03-26" "lsof 5.0" "System Diagnostic Tools"
.SH NAME
lsof \- list open files
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lsof
.RI [ OPTION ]...\&
.RI [ FILE ]...\&
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lsof
(List System Open Files) is a diagnostic tool that maps the topology between
processes and the files they hold open: regular files, directories, sockets,
pipes, devices, streams \(em anything the kernel touches.
.PP
If a process has a file descriptor,
.B lsof
sees it.
.PP
.B lsof
interfaces directly with kernel data structures.
Each target OS is a
.IR dialect " \(em"
a bespoke adapter wired into the machine layer.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Selection
.TP
.BR \-? ", " \-h
Display help.
.TP
.B \-a
AND selections (default: OR).
.TP
.BI \-c " COMMAND"
Select by command name (prefix, ^exclude, /regex/).
.TP
.BI +c " WIDTH"
Set COMMAND column width.
.TP
.BI \-d " FD"
Select by file descriptor set.
.TP
.BI \-g " [PGID]"
Exclude (^) or select process group IDs.
.TP
.BI \-p " PID"
Select by PID (comma-separated, ^excludes).
.TP
.BI \-u " USER"
Select by login name or UID (comma-separated, ^excludes).
.TP
.BI \-x " [fl]"
Cross over +d|+D file systems
.RB ( f )
or symbolic links
.RB ( l ).
.SS Network
.TP
.BI \-i " [ADDR]"
Select IPv4/6 files.
Address format:
.RI [ 46 ][ proto ][ @host|addr ][: svc|port ].
.TP
.B \-n
Inhibit host name resolution.
.TP
.B \-N
Select NFS files.
.TP
.B \-P
Inhibit port number to name conversion.
.TP
.BI \-s " [PROTO:STATE]"
Exclude (^) or select protocol states by name.
On systems without TCP/UDP state support, display file size instead.
.TP
.BI \-T " [LEVEL]"
Disable or select TCP/TPI info.
.TP
.B \-U
Select UNIX domain socket files.
.TP
.BR +M " | " \-M
Enable (+) or disable (\-) portmap registration reporting.
.SS Files & Directories
.TP
.BI +d " DIR"
List open files in
.IR DIR .
.TP
.BI +D " DIR"
Recursively list open files in
.IR DIR
(slow).
.TP
.BR +f " | " \-f
+filesystem or \-file names.
.TP
.BI +f " [cfgGn]"
File struct info: count, addr, flags, node (where supported).
.TP
.BI +L " [COUNT]" " | " \-L " [COUNT]"
List (+) or suppress (\-) link counts < COUNT.
.TP
.BI \-D " ACTION"
Device cache control
.RI ( ?|i|b|r|u[path] ).
.TP
.BI +e " PATH" " | " \-e " PATH"
Exempt filesystem (risky).
.SS Display
.TP
.BI \-F " [FIELDS]"
Select output fields for machine-readable mode.
Use
.B \-F \&?
for a list of available field IDs.
Fields include:
.B p
(PID),
.B c
(command),
.B f
(fd),
.B n
(name), and others.
.TP
.B \-l
Display UID numbers instead of login names.
.TP
.BI \-o " [DIGITS]"
Display file offset (0t format).
.TP
.B \-R
List parent PID (where supported).
.TP
.B \-t
Terse output (PID only).
.TP
.B \-v
Display version information.
.TP
.B \-V
Verbose search.
.TP
.BR +w " | " \-w
Enable (+) or suppress (\-) warnings.
.SS System
.TP
.B \-b
Avoid kernel blocks.
.TP
.B \-O
Avoid overhead of extra processing (risky).
.TP
.BI \-S " [SECONDS]"
stat(2) timeout.
.TP
.BI +r " [SECONDS]" " | " \-r " [SECONDS]"
Repeat mode: + until no files, \- forever.
Optional suffix:
.BI m fmt
for
.BR strftime (3)
markers.
.TP
.B \-C
Disable kernel name cache (where supported).
.TP
.BI \-k " FILE"
Kernel symbols file (where supported).
.TP
.B \-K
List tasks/threads (where supported).
.TP
.BI \-m " FILE"
Kernel memory file (where supported).
.TP
.BI +m " [FILE]"
Use or create mount supplement (where supported).
.TP
.BI \-z " [ZONE]"
Select by zone name (where supported).
.TP
.BI \-Z " [CONTEXT]"
Select by security context (where supported).
.TP
.B \-\-
End option processing.
.SH EXAMPLES
List all open files:
.PP
.RS
.B lsof
.RE
.PP
Who's holding port 8080:
.PP
.RS
.B lsof \-i :8080
.RE
.PP
What files does PID 1337 have open:
.PP
.RS
.B lsof \-p 1337
.RE
.PP
All network connections \(em TCP & UDP:
.PP
.RS
.B lsof \-i
.RE
.PP
Find who's using a specific file:
.PP
.RS
.B lsof /var/log/syslog
.RE
.PP
Trace a user's open files:
.PP
.RS
.B lsof \-u neo
.RE
.PP
Emit parseable field output:
.PP
.RS
.B lsof \-F pcfn
.RE
.SH FIELD OUTPUT
When invoked with
.BR \-F ,
.B lsof
produces machine-readable output.
Each field is preceded by a single-character ID:
.B p
(PID),
.B c
(command name),
.B f
(file descriptor),
.B n
(file name), among others.
Use
.B lsof \-F \&?
for the full list of field IDs available on your system.
.SH SUPPORTED DIALECTS
.B lsof
interfaces directly with kernel data structures.
Each target OS is a dialect \(em a bespoke adapter wired into the machine layer.
.PP
.TS
l l.
